title: ‘Blowouts’ throughout Victoria’s state budget
description: Deakin University Economist Dr Nataliya Ilyushina says Victoria’s state budget is “hard to understand”.  Victoria’s debt is out of control and continually increasing.  Ms Ilyushina told Sky News Australia that there is “blowouts” throughout the budget.

title: Australia’s economy can ‘no longer handle’ the number of migrants
description: Deakin University Economist Dr Nataliya Ilyushina discusses the current migration system “overemphasises” highly skilled individuals.  Ms Ilyushina said Australia’s economy can “no longer handle” the number of migrants coming to the country.  Australia’s housing supply is under stress as increased demand keeps prices up.

title: ‘The I in ISIS stands for Islamic’: Push to take religion out of terror laws
description: Former NSW police minister David Elliott criticises the Human Rights Commission for pushing to change the definition of terrorism in this country.    “The whole definition of extremism is people who have ideological and religious views that are beyond the pale or beyond what a reasonable or a sensible person would consider appropriate,” Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “Every religion has an extremist… the I in ISIS stands for Islamic, so we can not walk away from that.”

title: Australian intelligence agencies have not changed the ‘definition’ of a terrorist act.
description: NSW independent MP Tania Mihailuk says the Victorian Human Rights Commission, as well as the Human Rights Commission, have proposed to “remove religion” as a motivation in acts of terrorism.    “It would change the definition of terrorist act in its entirety if it were removed,” Ms Mihailuk told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “All the Australian agencies are saying there should not be any change to the definition of a terrorist act.”

title: Hold the ‘Mariah Carey songs’ during the Christmas season: David Elliott
description: Former NSW police minister David Elliott discusses his pet peeves during the Christmas season.  “I don't despise her, but it creates a lot of fuss in most offices working out how much is an appropriate level of Mariah Carey songs,” Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  ‘I still find it difficult to get excited about Christmas lights … I've nearly electrocuted myself so many times.” ​

title: ​ ‘Not responsible’ for public servants to work from home
description: NSW independent MP Tania Mihailuk states it’s “not responsible” when business investment and productivity are already “down” for most public servants to be working from home.  “That's taking away the resources that we need in the private sector,” Ms Mihailuk told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “When we really desperately need an investment to pick up our economy.”

title: ‘Typical socialist approach’: One in three public servants in office
description: Former NSW police minister David Elliott says his “concern” with remote workers is the “idea of fairness”.  This comes after it’s been revealed that only one in three public servants work full-time in the office.  “This is a typical socialist approach to the economy,” Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.

title: Complete ‘lack of empathy’ from Labor in parliament 2025 wrap
description: Liberal MP Mary Aldred says energy bills have increased by “40 per cent” under the Labor government.  “You might say that Chris Bowen and the PM are exceptionally pleased with the way they've turned out,” Ms Aldred told Sky News host Steve Price.  “But there just seems to be a complete lack of empathy, a complete divorce from the reality that many Australians are facing right now.”

title: ‘Part-time’ minister ‘flat-footed’ on increasing power bills
description: Liberal MP Mary Aldred calls out “part-time” Minister for Climate Change and Energy Chris Bowen for being “flat-footed” when questioned on the impact increasing power bills have on Australian lives.  “He's been promising for years and years that all of these renewable answers, they're all free … and benefitting,” Ms Aldred told Sky News host Steve Price.  “The reality is they're not. Emissions are flatlined.  “While they've thrown $75 billion at it.”

title: Timber industry ‘nearly killed off’ in Victoria: Liberal MP
description: Liberal MP Mary Aldred discusses the environment reform bill passed by the Australian Parliament.  “I'm particularly worried about our timber industry in Victoria,” Ms Aldred told Sky News host Steve Price.  “The state government, particularly Lily D'Ambrosio, have nearly killed off the timber industry through closing down the native hardwood sector.”

title: Jess Wilson’s ‘great plan’ to get Victoria ‘back on track’
description: Liberal MP Mary Aldred states the new Victorian Opposition Leader Jess Wilson has a “great plan” to get Victoria “back on track”.  “She’s going to focus on the economic mess … got the skills, the credibility,”  Ms Aldred told Sky News host Steve.  “I think she's going to make a great premier.”

title: ‘Mood for change’: Victorian Nationals target Premier’s Bendigo East seat
description: Victorian Nationals Leader Danny O'Brien states Premier Jacinta Allan's own seat of Bendigo East is a target for his party.  “We think the Nationals have got a really strong showing in a regional seat like Bendigo,” Mr O'Brien told Sky News host Steve Price.  “There's a mood for change right across regional Victoria.” ​

title: Vic Nationals Leader accuses Labor of abandoning regions that aren't ‘Melbourne’
description: Victorian Nationals Leader Danny O'Brien accuses the Labor government of abandoning regional Victorians.  “We've seen $50 billion of blowouts on the big projects in Melbourne… that have added to our debt and to the cost of interest we're all experiencing,” Mr O'Brien told Sky News host Steve Price.  “Regional Victorians literally are driving around on goat tracks … we've got terrible roads.” ​

title: Regional Victorians are ‘crying out’ for infrastructure investment
description: Victorian Nationals Leader Danny O'Brien says the new metro tunnel and other “big projects” for Melbourne will “rarely benefit” regional Victorians.  “It's certainly not going to be a great benefit for regional Victoria and the premier has tried to spin that a number of times,” Mr O'Brien told Sky News host Steve Price.  “We're crying out for infrastructure investment, whether it's in our roads, whether it's in our hospitals.”

title: ‘Discontent’ in regional Australia under the Labor government
description: Victorian Nationals Leader Danny O'Brien raises awareness of “discontent” in regional areas under the Labor government.  “There's discontent in rural areas, I think there's growing discontent even in the regional cities over the lack of attention,” Mr O'Brien told Sky News host Steve Price.  “We're heading for $29 million a day in interest payments under this government; imagine what that can do.”
